A new science
This summer, an unusual conference took place in Paris. There, researchers met to think about the necessity of a new science that could be just as revolutionary as Einstein's findings a hundred years ago.
The majority of scientists believe that the fundamental questions of science have been answered.
Considering the great challenges, one is of the opinion that there is little left to discover.
The remaining questions can be divided into three groups: Firstly, the great unsolved puzzles of science (such as the union of gravity and electricity in a theory), whose research requires enormous investments and the infrastructure of the First World. Secondly, data collection, which refers to work related to archaeological excavations and biological/genetic studies, and thirdly, problems whose solution will be based on scientific foundations, such as the fight against AIDS or global warming.
In addition, many think that the most difficult part of the job would be to use new technologies to benefit humanity by utilizing already known laws of nature.
Who could dispute that?
The models of today do work, anyway.
A growing group of scientists is pointing out phenomena that are not so well explained by current theories.
These problems are occurring more frequently, but they are also cleverly circumvented, because the science to explain these problems simply does not exist.
This missing science would describe processes and the emergence of entire systems.
In the individual scientific disciplines, the knowledge is reasonably well established.
Physics, at least the part with which we as ordinary mortals are confronted, is well researched.
Chemistry and biochemistry also stand on solid foundations - while there are still a few things in our body that we do not yet understand, it is assumed that the basic mechanisms of interaction between cells and molecules are known.
In addition, there are also the new social sciences that focus on people and societies.
In each of these fields – physics, biochemistry, and social sciences – the theories are well-established and largely uncontroversial.
Each discipline has its own language and its own mechanisms.
In the rarest cases, a scientist is an expert in more than one field, because these worlds and languages are so different from one another.
This means we cannot find an answer to complex questions that require the involvement of several disciplines.
For example, think of the brain.
This complex organ is composed of molecules whose interaction occurs based on the principles of physics. The information exchanged is transmitted due to the laws of electricity.
There is also a system of specialized cells that communicate through the exchange of chemical substances and also transmit information in the process.
During the interaction between two brains, a new level is added: here, information exchange takes place via language, signs and concepts.
It is about the exchange of information at every level, and there are suitable theories that explain the processes on each individual level.
Information is indeed exchanged between the individual levels, but there is no science that could even roughly explain this information exchange.
To compensate for this shortage, some scientists have tried to redefine the instrumentation for explaining processes within a plane in order to then apply it to another plane.
These attempts then lead to something like a "language" on a cellular level and "energy" behind organized societies.
Sometimes this "transplantation" of explanation patterns works quite well, but the underlying problem is not thereby solved: How is the information exchanged between the individual levels composed and how is it transmitted?
Now almost all systems of this world consist of such layers.
And in all cases, this shameful lack of knowledge of how the overall system works prevails.
The group of interdisciplinary scientists, who met in Paris, has informally formed itself under the name "Foundations of Information Science".
The researchers come from various countries and fields of expertise and have been working together on a decentralized basis for eight years.
Besides scientists from relevant disciplines, art theorists, psychiatrists, language experts and philosophers are also beginning to participate in the discourse.
The majority of the group opt for this "transplantation strategy", in which one adjusts and supplements the scientific foundations of a level to transfer them to another.
Others, on the other hand, consider a completely new approach to be necessary.
In their opinion, many scientific norms are the product of historical accidents and new ways of thinking are needed.
If the FIS Group is lucky, new radical approaches emerge from scientists who currently have no access to the infrastructure of the First World.
Unrestricted thinking is an underestimated factor.
Almost all activities that take place under the sign of "science" have, similarly to their counterparts from the world of economy, developed an institutional character.
People believe that developing countries should build similar resources as industrial countries. However, this could stifle creative thinking.
Many young scientists are currently experiencing a revolution and many of these – sometimes revolutionary – ideas come from laboratories and research centres that are not connected with the large institutions.
The most thoughtful approaches in the field of mathematical algorithms came from the Soviet Union for twenty years, where there was a shortage of computing capacity at every corner and end.
The most genius and, in the truest sense of the word, most groundbreaking insights in the field of physics over the past few decades did not come as expected from the known innovation centers but from Budapest.
In Iran, there is a tradition of architecture that has helped cognitive scientists gain important insights.
And the most radical new ideas in the area of second-generation artificial intelligence (so-called "autonomous agents") come today from Prague.
The most creative scientific achievements have entered history.
As Einstein expanded physics with a new way of thinking, it thereby changed the identity of space and time. The FIS conference in July was the unannounced beginning of an attempt to redefine the universe in this way.
Those gaps have been identified for which explanations must be found.
More scholars from innovative regions will be added to this group to then identify the problems that could be solved if this new science is developed or discovered, as one wishes.
